Elevator pitch

âWe all create stories to protect ourselves.â

-Mark Z. Danielewski, House of Leaves

Asbestos? Not a fan! It used to be all the rage in the mid-20th century as a cure-all and building material, and people made some serious money advertising its benefits and neglecting to study its other consequences. Once people started living around the stuff, it created serious health hazards. People donât built with it anymore, but there may still be homes on the market that are unknowingly built with asbestos material. Letâs predict which ones are as-best-os we can!

bathChart + my_line2

Thereâs a few types of houses that give us a pretty solid guess as to their year. Overall the more bathrooms it has, the more likely it is to be built recently. A majority of houses with 4 or more are built after 1980, which can help us narrow down our asbestos search.

Similarly to bathrooms, the number of floors can also be a good predictor. Older houses tend to be smaller, judging by the medians of our boxplots. These two also probably correlate, because who needs 6 bathrooms when you only have one floor!

5 1/2 Minute Hallway

Build a classification model labeling house as being built âbefore 1980â or âduring or after 1980â. Your goal is to reach or exceed 90% accuracy. Explain your final model choice (algorithm, tuning parameters, etc) and describe what other models you tried.

âWhat miracle is this? This giant tree.

It stands ten thousand feet high but doesnât reach the ground.

Still it stands.

Its roots must hold the sky.â -Mark Z. Danielewski, House of Leaves

I tried the Boost model, but it took a lot longer to run and ultimately gave me slightly weaker results than just our basic Decision Tree classifier.

My model uses a few variables from most of the categories available. There are some about the house features, like garage, living space, stories. I also used the condition of the house (Fair, Good) and the neighborhood it was in.

With 20 total variables, I tried to keep the depth of our classifier to below that amount, ending at 14 as my best indicator.

plot example 
# Include and execute your code here
features = df2.filter(['numbaths','stories','livearea','arstyle_CONVERSIONS','sprice','totunits','nocars','numbdrm','conditionGood','conditionFair','condition_AVG','gartype_Att','gartype_Det','gartype_None','quality_C','deduct','netprice','tasp','nbhd_1','nbhd_2','nbhd_3','nbhd_4','nbhd_5'])
targets = df2.before1980
train_data, test_data, train_targets, test_targets = train_test_split(features, targets, test_size=.34, random_state = 80)

classifier_DT = DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth = 14)
classifier_DT.fit(train_data, train_targets)
y_predicted_DT = classifier_DT.predict(test_data)
print("Accuracy:", metrics.accuracy_score(test_targets, y_predicted_DT))
Accuracy: 0.9094351530451247

table example 
# Include and execute your code here
classifier_DT.feature_importances_
features_df = pd.DataFrame({'features':test_data.columns,'importance':classifier_DT.feature_importances_})
ImportantChart = alt.Chart(features_df).encode(
    x=alt.X('features',sort='-y',axis=alt.Axis(title='What Features?')),
    y=alt.Y('importance',axis=alt.Axis(title='How Impactful Were they?',format='%')),
).mark_bar().properties(title='What\'s our Dream Home?')
ImportantChart

I was surprised by how much of an impact the number of stories had on when the house was built. Such a simple metric could do a pretty good job on its own. Between the different garage metrics, I wasnât too surprised by its impact, because the way Americans treat and see their cars (as well as the way cities are built to accomodate them) has changed a lot in the past several decades. We also saw that neighborhoods (nbhd_1, nbhd_2, etc) had a big imapct. My familyâs current house in Arizona is an old farm lot, and the rest of the town has slowly built up around these old, large lots. All the houses in our neighborhood were built around the same time, so we can expect a correlation between the houses.

âThis is not for you.â

Describe the quality of your classification model using 2-3 different evaluation metrics. You also need to explain how to interpret each of the evaluation metrics you use.

âHe turned to find himself staring at a new wall: concrete, grey, suffocating. The labyrinth was alive, and it had been disturbed.â -Mark Z. Danielewski, House of Leaves

Show the code 
print(pd.crosstab(test_targets, y_predicted_DT, rownames=['True'], colnames=['Predicted'], margins=True))
Predicted     0     1   All
True                       
0          3119   490  3609
1           371  5527  5898
All        3490  6017  9507

Here is the confusion matrix for our algorithm. Across the first row, we see that our specificity is \frac{3113}{(496+3113)} = 0.863 Our program correctly identified 86% of the post-1980 homes. It did a lot better recognizing the pre-1980 homes, scoring \frac{5529}{(369+5529)} = 0.937 for our Recall score. This means our model is slightly more likely to assume a house is unsafe to live in when it likely doesnât have asbestos. I think this is the safer option, because getting a second prediction or an in-person inspector is easier to rectify than the subtle but damaging effects of asbestos inhalation.
